"# Chapter 3 — Higher-Order

A higher-order function is a function that takes another function as an argument, returns a function as its result, or both. That sounds theoretical. It is not theoretical. It is what lets you write a function like `map` once and never write a `for` loop again. You already used higher-order functions in Chapter 2. This chapter names them and shows you how to build your own.

## Why this lib exists

Some code shapes are the same every time except for one detail. Sorting numbers ascending vs descending — same walk, different comparator. Timing a function call — same start-clock/call/stop-clock, different function. Retrying on failure — same retry loop, different action.

Without higher-order functions you copy the loop each time and edit the detail. With them, you write the loop once and pass the detail as an argument.

This chapter has four steps: use a built-in higher-order, write one, return one, and compose several.

## Problem 1 — Time how long a function takes

Motoi has a millisecond clock. Wrap any function in a timer:

```
(define (time-it label thunk)
  (let ((start (current-time-ms)))
    (thunk)
    (let ((elapsed (- (current-time-ms) start)))
      (display label)
      (display \": \")
      (display elapsed)
      (display \"ms\\n\"))))

(time-it \"count to a million\"
  (lambda ()
    (let loop ((n 0))
      (if (= n 1000000)
          'done
          (loop (+ n 1))))))
;; => count to a million: 12ms
```

Read the shape. `time-it` takes a label and a `thunk` — a function of no arguments. It notes the clock, calls the thunk, notes the clock again, prints. Anywhere you want to time some code, wrap it in `(lambda () ...)` and hand it over.

That `lambda ()` — no arguments in the parens — is the standard shape for `do this later`. Motoi will not run the body until someone calls the thunk. That is why the timer can straddle it.

## Problem 2 — Write your own `keep-if`, which is just `filter` with the arguments swapped

Some days you want the collection first and the predicate second. Rewriting `filter` from scratch teaches you the shape:

```
(define (keep-if lst pred)
  (cond ((null? lst) '())
        ((pred (car lst))
         (cons (car lst) (keep-if (cdr lst) pred)))
        (else
         (keep-if (cdr lst) pred))))

(display (keep-if (list 1 2 3 4 5 6) odd?))
;; => (1 3 5)
```

`keep-if` is a higher-order function — it takes `pred` (which is a function). It is also recursive: if the list is empty, return empty; if the first element passes the predicate, cons it onto the result of recursing on the rest; otherwise, skip it and recurse on the rest. Chapter 4 talks about recursion at length. Here, notice: the predicate is just an argument like any other.

## Problem 3 — A function that RETURNS a function

This is where things start to feel like magic and then stop feeling like magic. `adder` takes a number and returns a function that adds that number to whatever it is called with:

```
(define (adder n)
  (lambda (x) (+ x n)))

(define add-ten (adder 10))
(define add-hundred (adder 100))

(display (add-ten 5))       ;; => 15
(display (add-hundred 5))   ;; => 105
(display ((adder 42) 8))    ;; => 50
```

`adder` is a factory. Every call produces a fresh function. That function remembers the `n` from when it was made — Scheme people call that a closure, and it just means the inner function closes over the outer function's variable.

The last line, `((adder 42) 8)`, calls `adder` and immediately calls the result. Nothing stored. Same idea, more concise.

You use this pattern any time you want to build a specialized version of a general operation. `(adder 10)` is `+ 10`, permanent. In graphics you might write `(coloring 'pink)` that returns a function that draws a shape pink. Same shape.

## Problem 4 (pro) — Compose functions into a pipeline

Sometimes you want to say `first do A, then do B, then do C` and have the result be a single function you can call once. That is composition:

```
(define (compose2 f g)
  (lambda (x) (f (g x))))

(define add-one (lambda (n) (+ n 1)))
(define double  (lambda (n) (* n 2)))
(define square  (lambda (n) (* n n)))

(define do-all (compose2 square (compose2 double add-one)))

(display (do-all 3))
;; => 64
```

Trace it: `3` goes into `add-one`, becomes `4`. `4` goes into `double`, becomes `8`. `8` goes into `square`, becomes `64`. The function `do-all` bakes that whole pipeline into one callable value.

Now the general version — compose any number of functions:

```
(define (compose . fns)
  (if (null? fns)
      (lambda (x) x)
      (let ((first (car fns))
            (rest  (apply compose (cdr fns))))
        (lambda (x) (first (rest x))))))

(define do-all-nice (compose square double add-one))

(display (do-all-nice 3))
;; => 64
```

The `. fns` in the lambda list means `collect all the arguments into a list`. `apply compose (cdr fns)` calls `compose` again with the rest of the functions as separate arguments. The base case — no functions left — returns the identity function.

If you have never seen `apply` before: `apply f (list a b c)` is the same as `(f a b c)`. It spreads a list back into arguments. This is the bridge between variadic functions and lists.

## Capstone — A rate-limiter that lets a function fire at most once per interval

```
(define (rate-limit interval-ms fn)
  (let ((last-fire 0))
    (lambda args
      (let ((now (current-time-ms)))
        (if (< (- now last-fire) interval-ms)
            'throttled
            (begin
              (set! last-fire now)
              (apply fn args)))))))

(define greet (rate-limit 1000 (lambda (name)
                                  (display \"hi, \")
                                  (display name)
                                  (display \"\\n\")
                                  'greeted)))

(greet \"Alfred\")   ;; => hi, Alfred      ;; result: greeted
(greet \"Alfred\")   ;; => (no print)      ;; result: throttled
;; wait 1 second...
(greet \"Alfred\")   ;; => hi, Alfred      ;; result: greeted
```

Three ideas landed here. First: the outer `let` gives the returned function a private variable (`last-fire`) it can update between calls. That is a closure carrying state — a mutable cell only the returned function can see.

Second: `lambda args` collects all arguments into a list called `args`, so the returned function works no matter how many arguments the wrapped function takes.

Third: `apply fn args` calls the wrapped function with those arguments. The wrapper does not need to know what the wrapped function expects — it just passes everything through.

This pattern shows up everywhere. A debouncer is the same shape with the condition inverted. A memoizer is the same shape with a hash-table replacing `last-fire`. A logger is the same shape with `display` around the call. Once you see it, you see it everywhere.

## What's next

Chapter 4 slows down and talks about recursion — the pattern that made `compose` and `keep-if` work above. If you have been reading and nodding but the recursive calls made your eyes cross, Chapter 4 is where we walk through them one at a time.
")
